                <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1123 Seymour, Walter F./1: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-04-25T19:00:00+08:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">April 25, 1928—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 26—9:45 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>274. 1. Following from consul at Tsinanfu: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“April 25, noon. Mrs. Charles Eames at Tsingtau, wife of Presbyterian
                            missionary at Tsining, has received a telegram from Hsu-chowfu signed by
                            Hayes of the same mission at Tenghsien stating that: ‘Charles writes
                            soldiers 16th shot Dr. Seymour through heart. Others, including Baltzer
                            party, safe. All leaving Tsining when possible. Tenghsien quiet.’ No
                            further details available. Seymour is head of Presbyterian Hospital,
                            Tsining.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>2. The Legation is endeavoring to secure confirmation and details.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
